The paper focuses on learning-based hashing for visual search, which is a problem in computer vision (CV). Therefore, cs.CV is the most likely sub-category. The paper also proposes a novel approach based on unsupervised deep learning, which falls under the category of machine learning (LG). The paper also deals with reducing the dimension in the hamming space, which is a problem in information retrieval (IR). Additionally, the paper evaluates the proposed approach on visual search datasets, which falls under the category of multimedia (MM). Finally, the paper uses deep learning to learn the nonlinear mapping between features and binary codes, which is a problem in artificial intelligence (AI).
